pipeline_messages.content:
You are an expert writing quality judge. You will evaluate three drafts
against a set of personalized rubric criteria. You also have access to the user's
recent conversation history for additional context about their preferences.

The three drafts are:
- Draft A = the **rubric-guided** draft (written following the user's rubric criteria)
- Draft B = the **generic** draft (written with no rubric — just competent writing)
- Draft C = the **original preference** draft (written from the user's stated preferences, before the rubric was created)

DRAFT A (rubric-guided):
The door was heavier than I expected. That's the first thing. I almost walked past the place entirely — it had one of those facades that gives nothing away, just a dark curtain behind fogged glass and a handwritten sign I couldn't read. But there was a smell coming through the gap in the doorframe that stopped me on the sidewalk. Not broth, exactly. More like the memory of broth — something deep and mineral, like wet stone in a hot bath, and underneath it a faint char that made the back of my throat go warm before I'd even stepped inside.

I pushed through the curtain.

The room was small enough that every seat felt like the only seat. Six counter spots, a cook who didn't look up. A radio somewhere playing something that sounded like a weather report. The steam coming off a bowl in front of the guy two seats down had this slow, deliberate curl to it — almost ceremonial. I stood in the entrance for probably five seconds too long, dripping snow off my jacket onto the mat, and the cook still didn't look up. Not rude. Just unhurried. Like time in there moved at a different setting than the street outside.

I sat down. Unwrapped my scarf. Somewhere behind me, a timer clicked off.

I had no idea what I was ordering. I pointed at the guy's bowl and held up one finger, and the cook nodded once — this small, practiced acknowledgment — and that was the whole transaction. Which, honestly, is how most of my better decisions have happened. Pointing at things and hoping for the best.

DRAFT B (generic):
The smell hit me before the door had fully opened — not the aggressive, meaty cloud I'd braced for, but something quieter. Woodsmoke, maybe, or the ghost of it. Inside, the place was barely the size of a decent closet: eight seats, a low counter, one man working a ladle with the focused calm of someone who'd stopped needing to think about it years ago. Nobody looked up when I walked in. Not rudely — just because there was something else worth paying attention to. I almost left. Instead I found an empty stool, sat down, and tried to figure out what exactly was different about this room.

DRAFT C (original preference):
The door was heavier than I expected, and for a second I almost let it swing shut behind me and walk back out into the cold. That particular Sapporo cold — the kind that gets into your collar no matter how you've layered up. But then the smell hit me: miso and rendered fat and something almost caramelized underneath it all, warm in a way that felt less like a restaurant and more like someone's kitchen on a Sunday. The place was maybe eight seats. A man behind the counter didn't look up, just tilted a ladle slightly, like he already knew I was staying.

